---
import "../styles/global.css";
import Leaderboard from "../components/Leaderboard.tsx";
import type { BenchmarkData } from "../components/Leaderboard.tsx";
import data from "../data/benchmark-results.json";

const bench = data as BenchmarkData;
const generated = new Date(bench.generatedAt).toISOString().slice(0, 10);
---

<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta charset="utf-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1" />
    <title>fontbench</title>
    <meta
      name="description"
      content="A benchmark measuring whether vision models can identify a typeface from a rendered image."
    />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com" />
    <link rel="preconnect" href="https://fonts.gstatic.com" crossorigin />
    <link
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;500;600&family=JetBrains+Mono:wght@400;500&family=Space+Grotesk:wght@500;700&display=swap"
      rel="stylesheet"
    />
  </head>
  <body>
    <main class="shell">
      <Leaderboard data={bench} client:load />

      <article class="prose">
        <p class="prose__kicker">Methodology · {generated}</p>
        <h2>Reading the fine print of type</h2>
        <p>
          Most vision benchmarks reward semantic understanding: what the text says, what is in the
          scene. fontbench asks the opposite question. Telling Helvetica from Arial means reading
          terminal angles, aperture, the leg of an <code>R</code>, the tail of an <code>a</code>:
          high-frequency detail that vision encoders are trained to throw away. Every label is
          exact, because every image is rendered straight from a known font file.
        </p>

        <h3>The task</h3>
        <p>
          One rendered specimen, four candidate families, one answer. The model replies with a
          single letter and a confidence as strict JSON, so random chance sits at
          <code>{Math.round(bench.dataset.chance * 100)}%</code>. Distractors come from the same
          category first (sans, serif, mono), so the choices stay plausible.
        </p>

        <h3>The data</h3>
        <p>
          {bench.dataset.fonts} families, {bench.dataset.openFonts} open and
          {" "}{bench.dataset.proprietaryFonts} licensed (Arial, Helvetica Neue, Futura, Avenir
          Next, Proxima Nova, Times New Roman). Each renders across three diagnostic strings and
          two variants, for {bench.dataset.totalSamples} specimens. Images are anonymized PNGs with
          no font name in the file, path, or metadata.
        </p>

        <h3>The harness</h3>
        <p>
          Inference runs through the <a href="https://cursor.com/docs/sdk/typescript">Cursor SDK</a>
          {" "}inside an offline <a href="https://e2b.dev/docs">E2B</a> sandbox. The controller
          uploads only the images and the questions, never the answer key or the fonts, then scores
          the returned predictions locally. The model never sees a correct label, and proprietary
          font files never leave the host.
        </p>

        <h3>This run</h3>
        <p>
          The board aggregates {bench.dataset.seeds} random draws of 20 items
          ({bench.dataset.evaluatedSamples} per model). Every model saw the same items in each
          draw. Token and latency figures come straight from the Cursor SDK run result.
        </p>

        <h3>What this is not</h3>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <b>A stable ranking.</b> {bench.dataset.evaluatedSamples} items is an early signal;
            per-seed accuracy swings by twenty points.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>A provider comparison.</b> Cursor mediates routing and image packaging, so this is a
            Cursor SDK board, not raw OpenAI, Anthropic, or Google APIs.
          </li>
          <li>
            <b>A dollar cost.</b> Spend is billed inside Cursor; tokens stand in as the proxy.
          </li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Reproduce</h3>
        <p>
          Build the data with <code>bun run dataset:all</code>, then evaluate a model with
          {" "}<code>bun run e2b:eval -- --model gemini-3.1-pro --limit 20</code>.
        </p>
      </article>

      <p class="foot">fontbench {bench.version} · {generated}</p>
    </main>
  </body>
</html>
